### Question 2: Synchronization Using a Monitor

I will use a **Mesa-style monitor**. To avoid starvation among producers (specifically to prevent 1-item producers from jumping ahead of a waiting 2-item producer), I use a ticket-based queue for producers.

```pseudo
Monitor BoundedBuffer {
    struct item buffer[N];
    int in = 0, out = 0, count = 0;
    Condition can_produce, can_consume;

    // Ticket system to ensure FIFO order for producers to avoid starvation
    int next_prod_ticket = 0;
    int serving_prod_ticket = 0;

    Entry AddToBuffer(struct item *data, int n) {
        // Acquire a ticket to ensure FIFO order
        int my_ticket = next_prod_ticket++;

        // Wait until it's my turn AND there is enough space
        while (my_ticket != serving_prod_ticket || count + n > N) {
            can_produce.wait();
        }

        // Add items to the buffer (guaranteed non-interleaved as it's a monitor entry)
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            buffer[in] = data[i];
            in = (in + 1) % N;
        }
        count += n;

        // Move to the next producer in line
        serving_prod_ticket++;

        // Notify all because multiple processes might now be able to proceed
        can_produce.notifyAll();
        can_consume.notifyAll();
    }

    Entry RemoveFromBuffer(struct item *data) {
        // Wait until there is at least one item
        while (count == 0) {
            can_consume.wait();
        }

        // Remove one item
        *data = buffer[out];
        out = (out + 1) % N;
        count--;

        // Notify all to allow waiting producers (especially the one at head of line)
        // or other consumers to check the state.
        can_produce.notifyAll();
        can_consume.notifyAll();
    }
}
```

**Variables and Initialization:**
- `buffer[N]`: Array of `struct item` of size `N`.
- `in`, `out`, `count`: Integers initialized to `0`.
- `can_produce`, `can_consume`: Condition variables.
- `next_prod_ticket`, `serving_prod_ticket`: Integers initialized to `0`.

