### Question 3: Synchronization Using Semaphores

To avoid starvation and ensure fairness, I use an `entry_gate` semaphore to act as a FIFO queue for groups trying to enter the room. Only the group at the head of the gate can attempt to acquire the necessary whiteboards.

```pseudo
// Global Variables and Semaphores
Semaphore mutex = 1;          // Protects the shared variable 'available'
Semaphore entry_gate = 1;     // Ensures FIFO order for entering groups
Semaphore boards_avail = 0;   // Used to block groups until boards are released
int available = N;            // Total whiteboards available, N >= 3

void EnterRoom(int count) {
    // Wait for our turn in the entry queue
    wait(entry_gate);

    wait(mutex);
    // While there aren't enough boards, wait for releases
    while (available < count) {
        signal(mutex);
        wait(boards_avail);
        wait(mutex);
    }

    // Acquire the boards
    available -= count;
    signal(mutex);

    // Release the gate so the next group can try to enter
    signal(entry_gate);
}

void LeaveRoom(int count) {
    wait(mutex);
    // Release the boards
    available += count;

    // Signal the boards_avail semaphore for each board released.
    // This wakes up the group waiting at the head of the entry_gate.
    // They will check the 'available' count and proceed or wait again.
    for (int i = 0; i < count; i++) {
        signal(boards_avail);
    }

    signal(mutex);
}
```

**Initialization:**
- `mutex` = 1
- `entry_gate` = 1
- `boards_avail` = 0
- `available` = N (where N >= 3)

